        <div style="overflow:hidden">
                                                                                                                                
                                                                                                                                                                                                                              <div class="imageleft">
                              <img src="/sites/worldliteraturetoday.org/files/Galil-b.jpg" alt="" width="" height=""  border="1" />
                                                              <br/> 
                                <div class="phototagleft">
                                  
                                </div>
                                                          </div>
                                                                                            <p class="word-copy-lh-mb" style="line-height:normal;margin-bottom:12.0pt;margin-left:0in;margin-right:0in;margin-top:0in;"><strong>Lilach Galil</strong> is an award-winning writer and poet, writing in Hebrew. In 1994 she won Hebrew University of Jerusalem’s Harry Hershon Award for her short stories. <em>In Its Shadow</em> (published in Israel in 2009) is her third novel. In addition to her three novels, Galil has published two short-story collections, two poetry books, and a prose-poetry book. Her works have appeared in numerous Hebrew literary publications. Galil, who holds an MFA in creative writing from the University of Haifa, is also known for her inspiring nature writing retreats.</p>
                                            <div class="clear"></div>
                                                          
                                                                                              
                                                                                                                                    <div class="imageleft">
                              <img src="/sites/worldliteraturetoday.org/files/Peleg-b.jpg" alt="" width="150" height="150"  border="1" />
                                                              <br/> 
                                <div class="phototagleft">
                                  
                                </div>
                                                          </div>
                                                                                            <p class="word-copy-lh-mb" style="line-height:normal;margin-bottom:12.0pt;margin-left:0in;margin-right:0in;margin-top:0in;"><strong>Dana G. Peleg</strong> is a bilingual Hebrew/English writer and translator of prose and poetry. She won the 2018&nbsp;<a href="https://www.ibby.org/fileadmin/user_upload/HL_2018_RZ.pdf">IBBY Certification of Honor</a> for her translation of <em>Anna and the Swallow Man</em>, by Gavriel Savit. She’s published two short-story collections in Hebrew, and her first novel (<em>Giantess’ Hand</em>) came out in 2024 in Hebrew. Peleg’s works have appeared in Israeli literary publications as well as&nbsp;<a href="https://www.asymptotejournal.com/blog/2022/05/24/translation-tuesday-chemistry-lesson-by-hagit-zohara-mendrowski/#more-29376"><em>Asymptote</em></a> and <em>Porter Gulch Review</em>. Her first English title as a translator, Miriam Matzner Kenan’s&nbsp;<a href="https://www.amazon.com/Midlife-Momentum-Entering-Confidence-Optimism-ebook/dp/B0BYF4BFSZ/ref=sr_1_1?keywords=Miriam+Kenan&amp;qid=1683599535&amp;sr=8-1" target="_blank"><em>Midlife Momentum</em></a>, appeared in 2023.</p>
